16 WHEREAS, over 120 million young people between the ages of 15 and 24 cannot read or
17 write, with 61 percent of this group being women; and
18 WHEREAS, half of the children who are not in school live in conflict-ridden areas, and girls
19 make up 55 percent of this total; and
20 WHEREAS, nearly 70 million children worldwide lack access to basic education, and more
21 than half are girls, with evidence showing that educating a girl can break a cycle of poverty
22 in just one generation; and
23 WHEREAS, girls who receive an education marry later, have fewer children, earn higher
24 wages, and support healthier and more prosperous families, underscoring that the
25 empowerment of and investment in girls are key factors in breaking the cycle of
26 discrimination and violence, as well as promoting and protecting their full human rights; and
27 WHEREAS, girls with an extra year of education can earn 20 percent more as an adult, and
28 a child born to a mother who can read and write is 50 percent more likely to survive past the
29 age of five; moreover, educated mothers are more than twice as likely to send their children
30 to school; and
31 WHEREAS, the State of Georgia is blessed with hundreds of gifted girls and young women
32 whose full potential has yet to be fostered and developed; and
33 WHEREAS, education is the key to the empowerment of this state's girls and young women,
34 fostering the development of their minds and academic and leadership skills as well as
35 playing a vital role in shaping tomorrow's leaders; and
